        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1981-03-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1981-03-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="25"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d25">
                <head>25. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1"
                        >Haig</persName> to All Agency Heads<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d25fn1">Source: Reagan Library, European and Soviet Affairs
                        Directorate, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>: Records, 1983–1989,
                            <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName>, Secretary of State (1).
                        Limited Official Use.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1981-03-03">March 3, 1981</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Reciprocity in <rs corresp="rec7ZKvPwsbdUPpj2" type="topic">Bilateral
                            Relations</rs> with the Soviet Union</item>
                </list>
                <p>It is this Administration’s policy to ensure strict reciprocity in our dealings
                    with the Soviet Union. In order to implement such a policy, it is important that
                    there be close coordination among all Government agencies which engage in
                    bilateral dealings with the Soviets.</p>
                <p>It is also our intention to bring the <rs corresp="recD442AQ8Opa4Jcf"
                        type="topic">access</rs> of the Soviet Ambassador and other Soviet officials
                    to U.S. Government offices in Washington <pb facs="0090" n="59" xml:id="pg_59"/>
                    more nearly into balance with the <rs corresp="recD442AQ8Opa4Jcf" type="topic"
                        >access</rs> which we have to Soviet officials in the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>.</p>
                <p>I have asked that the Interagency Coordinating Committee on U.S.-Soviet Affairs
                        (<gloss target="#t_ICCUSA_1">ICCUSA</gloss>) coordinate questions of
                    reciprocity. I also would appreciate your designating an official of your agency
                    to coordinate your agency’s Soviet contacts with the Department of State’s
                    Office of Soviet Union Affairs. Our purpose is not to cut off these contacts but
                    to monitor them to ensure that <rs corresp="recD442AQ8Opa4Jcf" type="topic"
                        >access</rs> is reciprocal.</p>
                <p>The telephone numbers of the Office of Soviet Union Affairs are 632–8670,
                    632–8671, 632–8720, 632–1712 and 632–2137.</p>
                <p>Thank you for your cooperation.</p>
            </div>
